[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Torre Attack"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2025.01.31"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/43294327"]

1. -- { Welcome to the Lifetime Repertoire based on the exciting Torre Attack! The course is based on the famous Torre Attack, which is characterized by the moves d4, Nf3, and Bg5 (usually in this order). } ( { In particular, this course is a Lifetime Repertoire that covers any opening by Black against } 1.d4 { . And when I say everything, I mean EVERYTHING, including rare sidelines.

The opening is named after the Mexican GM Carlos Torre. The Torre Attack is played regularly by some top GMs, including the multiple-time World Champion Magnus Carlsen, and other top players such as Andreikin and Harikrishna. Nonetheless, the Torre Attack is not considered to be a main line, and thus is perfect to surprise your opponents!

You will see how the Torre Attack offers plenty of dynamic opportunities to outplay your opponents. It's also strategically sound, even if, in some cases, our main goal is to mate our opponent! Without further ado, let's get into the course!

Structure of the course
I have split the course into five main blocks, two of them devoted to the Main Torre Lines and the other three for setups that make it complicated for us to play our usual Torre setup, which I refer to as 'Anti-Torre'. Please bear in mind that in the Torre Attack, and in particular in this course, there are many transpositions, so we can easily transpose to the main Torre chapters from different move orders.

♔ Main Torre chapters with } 1...Nf6 {
Here is what I consider the two main Torre blocks of the course, both starting with } ( 1...Nf6 { (or via transpositions): Main Torre with ...e6: 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 , and the Fianchetto variation: ` rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 2 '  2...g6 3.Bg5 .

♔ Anti-Torre chapters
In this part I present the many Anti-Torre possibilities at Black's disposal, starting from either ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1 '  1...Nf6 , 1...d5 , or any other first move, including the Dutch with 1...f5 . These are the chapters devoted to the lines in which Black doesn't let us transpose to any of the main Torre chapters above. There are three main blocks: Anti-Torre with 1...Nf6 , Anti-Torre with 1...d5 , Alternatives to 1...Nf6 and 1...d5 .

Anti-Torre Lines
Unfortunately, it is hard to play the Torre Attack against all possible setups by Black. Still, this course offers the option to maximize that without compromising your position. The majority of the Anti-Torre setups involve either playing ...d5 or delaying the development of the g8-knight.

We'll explore different move orders in which we postpone our c1-bishop development (usually by playing c3) until we see how Black develops. In most cases, we can reach one of our main Torre lines, and in other cases, we'll have to play another variation. But don't worry! I've attempted to cover all options so you would feel comfortable in any type of position.

Compatibility with other Chessable courses
This course is fully self-contained and you can play against any reply by Black. Anyway, it's always useful to be able to surprise your opponent by being unpredictable. This course offers you the option to do that. } ) ) ( { Usually, we start with } 1.d4 { and 2.Nf3, and therefore we are still able to play main lines such as the Catalan with g3 (check out the latest Alvar Alonso's course!) , or even the Queen's Gambit by then playing c4 and Nc3 (Kamil Plichta's course is a good example) . This is quite useful, as this way we can prevent some lines that we are not comfortable with (e.g. some Nimzo-Indian) and even force our opponent to play lines they are not comfortable with.

Anyway, more than these courses, the Torre is fully compatible with many ideas of the London System (several courses on Chessable, such as those from Alex Banzea or Le Quang Liem) . You can see how we even develop our bishop to f4 or the h2-b8 diagonal in certain lines. Our setup is indeed very similar to that of the London System, differing solely on the placement of the dark-squared bishop. } { Of course, the Trompowsky ( 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 ) also shares some similarities, and we can reach some similar positions by transposition. Again, you can check the course of our friend Kamil Plichta on this opening!

Finally, just to mention that Chessable has another excellent course that covers the Torre Attack in detail  -  the 'Calm & Collected' course by FM Marko Makaj. You will see some similar lines and ideas covered in this course but essentially, we have followed a different approach, and even most lines would be completely different. Still, two courses on the Torre are always better than one! :)

Transpositions
This course will have A LOT of transpositions. To the point that it's impossible to cover them all. I've tried my best to explain that in the course but, more importantly, I've tried to share the main ideas so you would be comfortable transposing to some lines via different move orders. Both Black and White have flexibility in the order in which they develop their pieces, which sometimes may have an effect, but in other cases, we can just reach a transposition.

Also, Black can many times play ...h6 in most lines. In that case, we mostly retreat the bishop to h4, and this, of course, can lead to small differences in the arising positions. For instance, in one of the main Torre lines, one important idea is to play h4 before castling! By playing ...h6, Black can prevent these lines. Still, in most cases the ideas will be very similar, but we have to be aware of the potential small differences. } ) ( { Another advantage of the course is that you may trick your opponent into getting into Torre lines without knowing! For instance, I play very often } 1.Nf3 { in my games (and this is also the case for Réti or King's Indian Attack players) , but I'm often unsure what to play against the flexible } 1...Nf6 { . With this course, I can now play } 2.d4 { comfortably, likely transposing to some of the main Torre lines.

Engine-proof
All the lines have been thoroughly checked with engines. However, it is important to know that when we are playing non-mainstream systems, it is hard to get an advantage when Black plays accurately. In fact, there may be positions in which the engine slightly prefers Black. This is very rare, however, and I made sure to include all the plans and ideas so you feel more comfortable playing any type of position. My main purpose is to offer lines that, as a human (which I assume you are!) , are easier to play for White.

Alternative lines
Given that this is a Lifetime Repertoire, I've tried to offer alternatives in some of the most important variations of the course. There are a couple of critical lines in which Black can achieve equality with accurate play (chess is a draw with perfect play after all!) . In these cases, we have offered two alternatives: one that is more challenging and arguably would take time to master, and another that is simpler and can be played following some simple concepts, which is given as an alternative. The choice is yours.

In fact, at some point, you may want to learn the main and alternative variations, as it's important to remain flexible against a well-prepared opponent. Also, the proposed alternative lines may offer a more complete picture of the course. And this is all for now, hope you enjoy the rest of the course! :) } ) *

