1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 d5 { Black can also play ...d5 via a different move order, which would then likely transpose to this line. } 
4. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge2e3]} { Our first rule is to start developing our b1-knight before we move our c2 or e2-pawns. This is essential when Black has the possibility to play ...Ne4. Here, it doesn't seem to be the case, but ...h6 followed by ...g5 is always on the cards! Another reason is that depending on Black's reaction, we could play c4 (rare) or e4 (sometimes) in one go.

Finally, our usual reply against ...Qb6 ideas is Rb1, so having developed our knight comes in handy if that's a viable option for Black.

♔ Bottom line: Play Nbd2 before c3 or e3! } Be7 
5. c3 { Here, I recommend starting with c3 and not with e3, which is the most usual move order. The main reason is that in other lines, we are forced to play c3 earlier, and therefore, we'll reach transpositions this way. Also, in some lines in the course, we will also see how White manages to play e4 in one go, so that is another advantage. } ( { Anyway, we'll most likely transpose to } 5.e3 { , as there are no variations to take advantage of either move order, so it's mostly a matter of taste. } ) O-O 
6. e3 b6 
7. Bd3 Ba6 
8. Bc2 $5  ( 8.Bxa6 { is also possible, but we prefer to complicate the game and preserve our bishop, as it's a very important piece for harassing Black's king. The game is suddenly quite concrete, as we cannot castle, so we have to somehow make our Bc2 move work! } ) c5 
9. h4 { After Bc2, we need to go all-in, as we cannot castle kingside! Anyway, h4 is a standard weapon in our arsenal! } Nbd7 
10. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gh1h3]} { Our usual way to proceed. After this, we can continue with f4 or even Rh3. } Nxe5 
11. dxe5 Nd7 
12. f4! ( 12.Bf4 { is also fine, as is often the case in these positions, but } ) ( 12.f4 { is sharper and more ambitious! It's also the best move according to the engine. } ) h6 $6  { This is not accurate, and now White can get a decisive advantage. } 
13. Qh5 $18  {[%cal Gg5h6]} ( 13.Qh5 { White is winning, as Black cannot stop all our threats. Of course, Black cannot play } 13...hxg5 { because of } 14.Qh7 { checkmate! } ) *

