1. d4 Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 c5 { We are going to analyze lines with ...c5 and ...Qb6, including or excluding ...h6. The arising positions will be largely similar, but there are a few small details that may differ, and it is, therefore, worth studying the lines with and without ...h6 separately.

I've included these lines with ...Qb6 separately, as the lines are very concrete, involving pawn sacrifices (mostly the b2-pawn), which are very different from the main chapters based on somewhat quieter ideas. } 
