1. d4 Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 h6 { We have to keep in mind that Black can play ...h6 in many situations. Our usual response will be Bh4, but it's always good to consider the alternatives; there are a few differences between playing ...h6 earlier or not. } 
4. Bh4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { In this particular position, } 4.Bxf6 { is also a fine alternative followed by e4 and c3. However, Black remains solid and has an advantage long term due to the bishop pair. Because of this, I suggest sticking with our usual response. } ) c5 { This is one of the most energetic responses by Black, directly challenging our center and usual setup. } 
5. e3 { This is our response against ...c5 in most cases, as our main idea is to recapture on d4 with our e-pawn, but there are exceptions! } cxd4 { This precise move order is suggested by IM Yuriy Krykun in his Queen's Indian Defense course. It's indeed a direct way to play against our setup and the idea is to follow it up with ...Qb6 but, in our case, we have a logical answer (exd4) and also a surprise alternative (Nxd4). } 
6. exd4 Qb6 
7. Nbd2 Qxb2 { In most cases, we'll transpose to other lines in which Black takes later on d4, but there is one independent try for Black. } 
8. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1g1]} { We continue in our usual fashion and plan to castle next. With this precise move order, we cannot play the intermezzo Rb1 that we play in a similar position when Black takes on d4. Anyway, we can get an interesting game. } Be7 
9. O-O Qb6 { This is the recommendation of IM Yuriy Krykun in his Chessable course, but here we have a surprise. } 
10. Re1 $146  ( { Only } 10.c4 { was covered in the course, but I feel this move order is a bit more accurate, although it will probably transpose. } ) O-O 
11. c4 {[%cal Gd4d5]} { Now we can play c4, and it's clear that Black will have problems completing their development. We are planning d5, so let's see what happens if Black plays ...d5 themselves. } d5 
12. Rb1 Qd8 { The safest square for the queen, and our response will be similar to other queen moves. } 
13. Ne5 $36  ( 13.Ne5 { Keeping up the pressure. If now } 13...Nc6 14.Nxc6 bxc6 15.c5 { with a clear advantage. } ) ( 13.Ne5 { In case Black eliminates the tension with } 13...dxc4 { , after } 14.Ndxc4 Nd5 15.Bxe7 { , White has an easy attacking plan (Rb3 or Bc2 followed by Qd3, and if Black defends with ...f5, Bb3 is also an idea) , while Black gets the pleasure of having to defend accurately. } ) *

