1. d4 Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 h6 { We have to keep in mind that Black can play ...h6 in many situations. Our usual response will be Bh4, but it's always good to consider the alternatives; there are a few differences between playing ...h6 earlier or not. } 
4. Bh4 ( { In this particular position, } 4.Bxf6 { is also a fine alternative followed by e4 and c3. However, Black remains solid and has an advantage long term due to the bishop pair. Because of this, I suggest sticking with our usual response. } ) c5 { This is one of the most energetic responses by Black, directly challenging our center and usual setup. } 
5. e3 { This is our response against ...c5 in most cases, as our main idea is to recapture on d4 with our e-pawn, but there are exceptions! } Qb6 { Black plays an early ...Qb6 to slow down our development. We can reach this position with or without ...h6 and Bh4 included. Our response will be similar in both cases. } 
6. Nbd2 {[%mdl 32768]} { This is the move I'm recommending against this early ...Qb6 setup. This is also the reason why I decided to include this early queen attack, as it's very different from other positions that we are going to see in the course. If Black gave us a tempo, we could play Rb1 and we would be fine.

With this move order, we are forced to sacrifice a pawn if we want to keep our usual setup. Don't worry, though; we'll get plenty of compensation! Also, we are covering all tricky move orders so you can be well prepared and understand all subtleties. } Qxb2 { The critical move, grabbing the pawn. Otherwise, we can just play Rb1, defending the pawn. } 
7. Bd3 { There are a few differences with the line in which ...h6 and Bh4 haven't been played. Nonetheless, in general terms, our idea is similar. We want to develop quickly in order to get a grip in the center, while Black will have to waste quite a few tempi with their queen. } d5 
8. Bxf6 { Here we take on f6, which we usually don't do without ...h6 included. With ...h6 included, Black has the possibility of playing ...g5 in one move, so we can get rid of that possibility entirely. } gxf6 
9. c4 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ga1b1,Gc4d5]} { Challenging the center, with a double-edged position where White is not worse. Rb1 and O-O are usually moves that we want to play, as well as cxd5. } dxc4 
10. Rb1 Qc3 { This is forced, as otherwise Nxc4 would be strong, limiting the mobility of Black's queen. } 
11. Bxc4 $16  {[%cal Gd4d5,Ge1g1]} { White is on top; O-O or d5 is usually next. } *

