5. Be3 ( { I'd like to recommend this 'rare' move. } 5.b4 { is the main move in this position, but the positions after } 5...a5 { , and eventually ...b6, become too double-edged to my taste. We've now reached an important crossroads, as Black has several options at their disposal. } ) a5 {[%cal Gb8a6]} { The most commonly played move in this position. The idea is clear: preventing us from playing b4 and expanding on the queenside. The next move is probably ...Na6. } 
6. c4 { Striking in the center before Black regains the pawn! Moves such as Nbd2 or g3 are also possible, but I like this direct approach in the center. Our queenside knight will now probably develop via c3, exploiting the b5-weakness created with the ...a5 pawn push. } Na6 
