3. Bg5 d5 { This is the starting position of this chapter. Black can also play ...d5 via a different move order, which would then likely transpose to this chapter. } 
4. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge2e3]} { Our first rule is to start developing our b1-knight before we move our c2 or e2-pawns. This is essential when Black has the possibility to play ...Ne4. Here, it doesn't seem to be the case, but ...h6 followed by ...g5 is always on the cards! Another reason is that depending on Black's reaction, we could play c4 (rare) or e4 (sometimes) in one go.

Finally, our usual reply against ...Qb6 ideas is Rb1, so having developed our knight comes in handy if that's a viable option for Black.

♔ Bottom line: Play Nbd2 before c3 or e3! } Be7 
5. c3 { Here, I recommend starting with c3 and not with e3, which is the most usual move order. The main reason is that in other lines we are forced to play c3 earlier, and therefore we'll reach transpositions this way. Also, in some lines in the course, we have also seen how White manages to play e4 in one go, so that is another advantage. } ( { Anyway, we'll most likely transpose to } 5.e3 { , as there are no lines to take advantage of either move order, so it's mostly a matter of taste. } ) b6 { It is also possible for Black to delay castling. } 
6. e3 Bb7 
7. Bd3 Ne4 { Black has developed in a way that ...Ne4 is now possible. This is definitely interesting, but nothing to be afraid of, and we have a strong continuation, taking advantage of Black's delayed castling. } 
8. Bxe7 Qxe7 
9. Qa4+ Bc6 { This is not the best square for the bishop. } 
10. Qc2 Nxd2 
11. Nxd2 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf2f4]} { Taking with the knight is more accurate; we're planning a future e4 break, or simply playing f4. Also, Black will have to spend a tempo for castling, as h7 is under attack. } Bb7 
12. O-O Nd7 
13. b4 $5  {[%cal Ga2a4]} { This is another idea at White's disposal, in addition to the usual f4 and Nf3, which would also be possible in this position. In this case, however, given that Black will have a hard time castling, we can expand on the queenside quickly; a4 is usually next. } c5 
14. bxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} bxc5 
15. Rab1 $14  {[%csl Rb7,Re8]} { White has a nice position. } *

