[Black "1...Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 d5 4.Nbd2 Be7 #24"]
[Date "2025.01.31"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A46"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/43294391"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 d5 { This is the starting position of this chapter. Black can also play ...d5 via a different move order, which would then likely transpose to this chapter. } 
4. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge2e3]} { Our first rule is to start developing our b1-knight before we move our c2 or e2-pawns. This is essential when Black has the possibility to play ...Ne4. Here, it doesn't seem to be the case, but ...h6 followed by ...g5 is always on the cards! Another reason is that depending on Black's reaction, we could play c4 (rare) or e4 (sometimes) in one go.

Finally, our usual reply against ...Qb6 ideas is Rb1, so having developed our knight comes in handy if that's a viable option for Black.

♔ Bottom line: Play Nbd2 before c3 or e3! } Be7 
5. c3 { Here, I recommend starting with c3 and not with e3, which is the most usual move order. The main reason is that in other lines we are forced to play c3 earlier, and therefore we'll reach transpositions this way. Also, in some lines in the course, we have also seen how White manages to play e4 in one go, so that is another advantage. } ( { Anyway, we'll most likely transpose to } 5.e3 { , as there are no lines to take advantage of either move order, so it's mostly a matter of taste. } ) O-O 
6. e3 b6 
7. Bd3 Bb7 
8. h4 $146  {[%cal Gg5f6,Gf3g5]} { This is our surprising move against this setup! The move is a novelty and a strong one! Since Black hasn't played ...c5 yet, Ne5 is a bit less effective. Also, we take advantage of the fact that we haven't castled yet, and we go all-in with the attack! One dangerous idea now is to play Bxf6 followed up by Ng5. } Ne4 { This is one of the main ideas of Black when playing with ...b6 and ...Bb7. Now we have several fine ways to continue. } 
9. Bf4 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gf3g5]} { This is the simplest move. We don't want to exchange pieces when we are attacking, so we retreat our bishop to f4. Also, the g5-square can be occupied by our knight, which would pose more threats; Qc2 or Ng5 are usually next. } Bd6 { Black continues harassing our bishop! } 
10. Ng5 {[%mdl 32768]} { Not the only move, but the most direct one! } Bxf4 { This is almost forced to get a playable position. } 
11. exf4 {[%cal Gd1c2][%csl Re4]} { The knight on e4 is under pressure, and Black doesn't have a good way to defend it. } Nf6 
12. Ndf3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd1c2]} { Bringing more wood to the fire! Black is under immense pressure. } h6 
13. Ne5 $16  {[%cal Gd1c2,Gd3h7]} { Of course, we don't want to retreat our g5-knight! White is almost winning at this point. Qc2 is usually next with a deadly threat of Bh7 followed by Nxf7. } *

