Hope you enjoyed this dynamic chapter, arguably the most important one in the whole course! } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Torre Attack"]
[White "2) Queen's Indian Setup 3...b6"]
[Black "Queen's Indian Setup 3...b6 4.Nbd2 h6 #1"]
[Date "2025.01.31"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A46"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/43294479"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 b6 ( { This is one of the main alternatives for Black, in line with a standard Queen's Indian setup. For the sake of simplicity, we are going to use this move order, but it's much more frequent to start with } 3...h6 { and then ...Bb7 in order to avoid ` rnbqkb1r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/6B1/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 4 '  4.e4 (a line which I don't recommend in this course). } ) ( { It's also possible to start with } 3...c5 { (or 4...c5 after 3...h6 for that matter!) and then Black eventually would play ...b6. In our case, it doesn't change much, as all these move orders will transpose to lines analyzed in this chapter. } ) 
4. Nbd2 {[%mdl 32768]} ( 4.e4 { is also possible, and it's indeed a good move, but I suggest we stick to our usual Torre-like setup for simplicity, as we will transpose to lines with an earlier ...h6.

As a general rule, we won't be playing e4 if doing so allows Black to force us to get rid of our dark-squared bishop with ...h6. This is mainly for simplicity as otherwise, we would need to learn two systems given that Black would always have the option to play an earlier ...h6. Also, this rule can be broken at times depending on Black's play. } ) h6 
5. Bh4 g5 
6. Bg3 Nh5 { We have now several fine alternatives. } 
7. e4 $14  {[%cal Gc2c3]} { I believe this standard way to respond is good enough. We will control the center in exchange for the bishop pair. Black will sooner or later play ...Bb7 so this move order doesn't have much of an independent value. } *

