3. Bg5 b6 ( { This is one of the main alternatives for Black, in line with a standard Queen's Indian setup. For the sake of simplicity, we are going to use this move order, but it's much more frequent to start with } 3...h6 { and then ...Bb7 in order to avoid ` rnbqkb1r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/6B1/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 4 '  4.e4 (a line which I don't recommend in this course). } ) ( { It's also possible to start with } 3...c5 { (or 4...c5 after 3...h6 for that matter!) and then Black eventually would play ...b6. In our case, it doesn't change much, as all these move orders will transpose to lines analyzed in this chapter. } ) 
4. Nbd2 ( 4.e4 { is also possible, and it's indeed a good move, but I suggest we stick to our usual Torre-like setup for simplicity, as we will transpose to lines with an earlier ...h6.

As a general rule, we won't be playing e4 if doing so allows Black to force us to get rid of our dark-squared bishop with ...h6. This is mainly for simplicity as otherwise, we would need to learn two systems given that Black would always have the option to play an earlier ...h6. Also, this rule can be broken at times depending on Black's play. } ) Bb7 { This is the most principled continuation, targeting White's center. However, there are also lines in which Black delays this move and plays ...Ba6 in one move. We'll also check those sidelines separately. } 
5. c3 { This is my suggested move order, which you should know well by now. In most cases, this will transpose to lines starting with e3, but in other cases, we may be able to play e4 in one go! Note that this move is played only in 6% of the games reaching this position, so it's likely that Black will be less familiar with this move order. } c5 
6. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3]} { Establishing our usual triangle in the center; Bd3 is usually next. } Be7 
7. Bd3 h6 
8. Bh4 O-O 
9. Qe2 { We can play this generally useful waiting move to see how Black develops. As usual, we may want to castle short or long depending on Black's reaction. In most cases, we may want to castle long anyway, especially since Black has already castled kingside. } d6 
10. Rg1 $146  {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Ge1c1]} { I like this move, which is a novelty and possible because Black has played ...h6 (hence creating a friction point on g5) and Black has already castled. Our plan is clear: g4, g5, and mating Black's king! } Nbd7 
11. g4 g6 { This is a difficult move to make, but it's probably the best defensive resource. The idea is to meet g5 with ...Nh7 and our bishop would be hanging on h4. } 
12. O-O-O $40  {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gh4f6,Gc1b1]} { We are not in a hurry and we can simply castle long. We have different ways to continue the attack, one of them being to take on f6 followed by g5. } *

