3. Bg5 { We've reached the main Torre position. In this chapter, we are going to analyze lines with ...c5 and ...Qb6, including or excluding ...h6. The arising positions will be largely similar, but there are a few small details that may differ, and it is, therefore, worth studying the lines with and without ...h6 separately.

I've included these lines with ...Qb6 in a separate chapter, as the lines are very concrete, involving pawn sacrifices (mostly the b2-pawn), which are very different from the main chapters based on somewhat quieter ideas. } c5 
4. e3 Qb6 { This is one of the main lines in the chapter. This precise move order is tricky, as we cannot react with our usual Rb1 (or not even Qc2/b3). Therefore, it's important to remember this move order. } 
5. Nbd2 { This is one of the very few lines where I'm recommending sacrificing the b2-pawn. It's a very concrete move order, but it's important to remember it in case we face it. If Black doesn't take on b2, we don't have any problems, as we can continue with our usual Rb1 response and get into well-known lines. } Qxb2 
6. Bd3 { In the line where Black plays ...cxd4 first, we have the additional possibility of starting with Rb1. } ( { Here, it wouldn't be that effective because of the following line: } 6.Rb1 Qxa2 7.Nc4 $6 Qa4 8.Bd3 b5! { and Black can follow it up with ...c4, which wouldn't be possible if the c- and d-pawns had already been exchanged. } ) cxd4 { This is always a possibility, and by using this move order, Black has prevented Rb1 and Nc4 ideas. } 
7. Rb1 $5  ( 7.exd4 { is also possible, but it's more interesting to play this move, to force Black to decide where to place their queen. } ) Qa3 
8. exd4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 
9. O-O { As usual, we are not in a hurry, so we just complete our development and see where Black places their pieces before we react. Note that our king is safely castled, which is important in most arising positions where the center may open up. } Be7 
10. Ne5 $14  ( 10.Ne5 { Only a pawn down, but White is active across the board. Note that } 10...O-O $4 { would already be a losing mistake because after } 11.Bxf6 { followed by Rb3 and a sacrifice on h7, White is suddenly winning! } ) *

