2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} { We've reached the main Torre position. In this chapter, we are going to analyze lines with ...c5 and ...Qb6, including or excluding ...h6. The arising positions will be largely similar, but there are a few small details that may differ, and it is, therefore, worth studying the lines with and without ...h6 separately.

I've included these lines with ...Qb6 in a separate chapter, as the lines are very concrete, involving pawn sacrifices (mostly the b2-pawn), which are very different from the main chapters based on somewhat quieter ideas. } h6 { We have to keep in mind that Black can play ...h6 in many situations. Our usual response will be Bh4, but it's always good to consider the alternatives. In the context of this particular chapter, there are a few differences between playing ...h6 earlier or not. } 
4. Bh4 ( { In this particular position, } 4.Bxf6 { is also a fine alternative followed by e4 and c3. However, Black remains solid and has an advantage long term due to the bishop pair. Because of this, I suggest sticking with our usual response. } ) c5 { This is one of the most energetic responses by Black, directly challenging our center and usual setup. } 
