1. d4 Nf6 
2. Nf3 c5 
3. d5 {[%mdl 32768]} { This is the direct way to challenge this move order. Depending on how Black proceeds, you can also transpose to Benoni or Benko lines, but I'm going to suggest some fresh ideas that do not involve c4 (so no need to study Benoni or Benko!). } e6 ( 3...e6 { The standard Benoni-like move. In fact, } 4.c4 { would now transpose to a usual Benoni position, but we are not going to do that! Still, for those players who are comfortable transposing to a Benoni, that would be a very reasonable option. } ) 
4. Nc3 { This is the main concept of our setup. Instead of c4, we are going to play with a quick Nc3 and eventually e4. } d6 $6  { This move isn't overly ambitious; we can control the center easily. } 
5. e4 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge4d5]} { Of course, we can now play e4 in good conditions. If Black were to take on d5, we would take with the pawn. } Be7 
6. Bb5+ { This check is useful to disrupt Black's normal development. } Bd7 { Now the black bishop is on a suboptimal square, and this will make it more complicated for Black to develop. } ( 6...Nbd7 $4 { Surprisingly, this move is already losing for Black! } 7.dxe6 fxe6 8.Ng5 $18 { and there is no way to defend e6. White is winning. } ) 
7. Bc4 e5 { Closing the position, but White still has several good ways to continue and claim a clear advantage. } 
8. O-O O-O 
9. a4 {[%cal Gf3d2]} { Our next move is Nd2, looking to reroute to c4. In the meantime, White can organize their pieces and plan a possible attack on the kingside. In contrast, Black's position is cramped, and they don't have a clear plan. There is only one way for Black to stop our plans, at least temporarily! } Bg4 { This pin isn't very dangerous, and indeed, there are several ways for us to continue. } 
10. Be2 $16  {[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4]} { I feel this is the simplest. We don't mind exchanging our light-squared bishop, so we'll continue with Nd2 if Black doesn't take on f3. White is clearly better. } *

