3. d5 { This is the direct way to challenge this move order. Depending on how Black proceeds, you can also transpose to Benoni or Benko lines, but I'm going to suggest some fresh ideas that do not involve c4 (so no need to study Benoni or Benko!). } b5 { The main Black's response against our setup, which makes a lot of sense. Black expands on the queenside and makes c4 more difficult, which we were not planning to do anyway! :) } 
4. Bg5 { We need to be quick since Black was planning to play ...Bb7, which would put pressure on our d5-pawn (as e4 and c4 are not possible). With Bg5, we develop our bishop to our preferred square and put pressure on Black's knight. } d6 
5. e4 $5  {[%csl Rb5,Re4]} { An interesting move to quickly take over the initiative! It isn't really a pawn sacrifice, as Black's b5-pawn is also hanging. } a6 
6. Nbd2 ( 6.a4 { could now have been responded with } 6...Nxe4 { , with a somewhat messy position. } ) g6 
7. a4 { We are already familiar with this pawn break! Now Black has to make a decision. } b4 
8. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gd2c4,Ge1g1]} { As with the previous variation, our bishop stands well on d3, overprotecting e4 and hence freeing our knight on d2. } Bg7 
9. O-O O-O 
10. Nc4 $16  {[%cal Ga4a5,Gd1e2]} { Our position is very comfortable with no weaknesses and active pieces. On the contrary, Black doesn't have much space and has some weaknesses.

This is the end of this chapter! Unlike other chapters, our idea is to quickly advance our pawn to d5 to restrict Black's play. In most cases, we can continue with pawn breaks on the queenside, such as a4, and at the same time conquer the center with e4. Overall, White stands better in most variations. } *

