1. d4 d5 
2. Nf3 Nf6 { We can reach this position via two (or more!) move orders. The main ones in our repertoire are ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 or ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 d5 . Similarly, for Réti players, this move can be reached starting with ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.Nf3 . } 
3. c3 ( { I wanted to recommend } 3.Bg5 { here, which goes more with the spirit of the Torre Attack. However, I couldn't find anything after } 3...Ne4 { , which is what I recommend in my Chessable course for Black, Queen's Gambit Declined.

Therefore, I decided to suggest this unexplored move, which is quite rare (played less than 1% of all games at the master level) but gives us very good options to transpose to our beloved Torre Attack. And even if we cannot transpose, I found some fresh ideas worth checking out! } ) c5 { This move directly challenges our plans to establish our usual Torre-like setup with Bg5 and e3. It is also a move that players familiar with the Tarrasch Defense will likely be inclined to play. } 
4. dxc5 { I recommend this direct approach. If Black is not careful, we will keep our extra pawn and start an expansion on the queenside. } ( { Note that similarly to the third move, } 4.Bg5 Ne4! { can be annoying, as Black hasn't played ...e6 yet (in fact, Black would already be slightly better in that position). This is something we are not particularly keen to allow. } ) e6 { This is the main move to try and regain the lost pawn. It has the drawback of closing the c8-h3 diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop. } 
5. Be3 ( { I'd like to recommend this 'rare' move. } 5.b4 { is the main move in this position, but the positions after } 5...a5 { , and eventually ...b6, become too double-edged to my taste. We've now reached an important crossroads in this chapter, as Black has several options at their disposal. } ) Nbd7 
6. b4 {[%mdl 32768]} a5 
7. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge3d4,Ge3g5,Ge3f4]} ( { It's very important to start with this move and not with } 7.g3? { After g3, Black can continue with } 7...axb4 8.cxb4 b6! { and Black is suddenly better. The key is that } 9.c6 { is not possible because of } 9...Bxb4+ { (with check). Our main idea is now to move our e3-bishop to another more useful diagonal since c5 is now well-defended by the b4-pawn. } ) Qc7 { This is perhaps the only move that we need to check carefully, as it prevents us from moving our bishop to d4 or f4, and also, Bg5 is less effective. } ( 7...Qc7 { We should be careful not to play } 8.g3 { , as } 8...Ng4 { would be now quite strong. } ) 
8. a3 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg2g3]} { We simply solidify our queenside pawns before proceeding with other operations. We will then slowly proceed with h3, g3, Bg2, and O-O. Rc1 is also a possible move now that it no longer needs to defend the a2-pawn. } Be7 
9. h3 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1]} O-O 
10. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1]} { We keep our extra pawn, although Black has some compensation. Let's see the most direct continuation by Black. } b6 
11. cxb6 { Forced. } Qxc3 
12. Bg2 {[%cal Ge1g1]} { The position is very concrete. Our main idea is to castle next. } axb4 
13. a4 $36  {[%cal Ge1g1]} { The position is quite double-edged, but it's Black who has to be especially careful given our potentially connected passed pawns. We'll castle shortly and then start harassing Black's queen. } *

