1. d4 d5 
2. Nf3 Nf6 { We can reach this position via two (or more!) move orders. The main ones in our repertoire are ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 or ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 d5 . Similarly, for Réti players, this move can be reached starting with ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.Nf3 . } 
3. c3 ( { Against 1...d5 setups, this is going to be our main move order. Our idea is simple: we want to postpone our known Torre lines with Bg5. The direct } 3.Bg5 { is also fully playable but would allow } 3...Ne4 { for Black, with easy play. } { We only cover the 3.c3 move order in this course, against both ` rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2 '  2...Nf6 or 2...e6 after 1...d5. } ) e6 
4. Bg5 { This is the starting position of this chapter. It can also be reached via the ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 e6 3.c3 Nf6 4.Bg5 move order. The main testing move to our setup is 4...h6 followed by ...g5 and ...Ne4. Any other move will directly transpose to our main Torre lines against ...Nf6 and ...e6. } h6 
5. Bh4 ( { As usual, we will respond to ...h6 with } 5.Bh4 { . } ) ( 5.Bxf6 { is certainly possible and is interesting on its own if you want to avoid the complications that will arise after Bh4 and ...g5. However, the positions tend to transpose to some variations featured in the French Defense (with White continuing with Nbd2 and a quick e4) where Black can equalize in several ways. } ) ( { While we recommend } 5.Bh4 { in the course, we also offer } ) ( 5.Bxf6 { as an alternative [/variation/43294907/#/5/w] for players who prefer this solid continuation. } ) g5 { This is the main idea of this particular move order. Because of the particularities of this move order, we have started with c3 instead of the usual Nbd2 of the Main Torre lines. } { This opens up the possibility of ` rnbqkb1r/ppp2p2/4pn1p/3p2p1/3P4/2P2NB1/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6 '  6...Ne4 for Black, which wouldn't be possible with our knight already on d2. In fact, this is the recipe against the Torre in the excellent Chessable courses of Max Warmerdam and Christof Sielecki. However, this is not to be feared for three reasons:

1. This position has been reached 5 times in total in the whole Masters database, including OTB games of 2200+ FIDE-rated players. In fact, 5...g5 is played less than 30% of all games that reached this position.

2. Even in the Chessable courses mentioned above, the line is not studied in-depth, and in fact, in both cases, the analysis stops after move 7.

3. We'll reach a very interesting position by force, with chances for both sides in which we'll understand all the ideas better than our opponent. } 
6. Bg3 Ne4 { The key idea  -  Black is taking advantage of the fact that we haven't played Nbd2 to cover the e4-square yet. } 
7. Nfd2 ( { This move was absolutely forced. } 7.Nbd2? h5! { and White is in trouble, as there is no easy way to defend against the ...h4 threat. } ) Nxg3 { This move is also forced for Black not to end up in a worse position. } 
8. hxg3 { We've reached the main position of this chapter. It is very important to understand this arising double-edged position well, as this is the usual recommendation against our move order (e.g., this is the recommendation in both Max Warmerdam's and Christof Sielecki's Chessable courses for Black). Nonetheless, this position has been reached very few times in practice.

Given our rare move order, Black is unlikely to be familiar with this position. In other words, this position is very important from the theoretical perspective, but we will rarely face it in practice, particularly for levels below GM. For instance, only 30 games have reached this position in the whole Lichess game database.

We've also arrived at a crossroads after the last forced moves for both sides. The position is healthy for Black who has several ways to continue. Nonetheless, the position is not without risk, especially if we do not understand them well, and we can try to pose problems if Black is not careful. } c5 { This is the main move recommended by Christof Sielecki. It makes a lot of sense, as Black puts pressure on our center and makes e4 more complicated. } 
9. Nb3 $146  { The most forcing move! It seems weird to move this knight once again while pieces are not developed, but there are very concrete reasons. } ( 9.e3 { is also possible, but it's a bit slow and leads to positions where Black's play becomes simpler, with the idea of ...Nc6, ...Bd7 and quickly castling queenside. } ) c4 { It's probably the best move for Black, but it has the clear drawback of releasing all the tension in the center. } 
10. N3d2 {[%cal Gb2b3,Ge2e4]} { And back to d2. :) It appears as if we may have lost two tempi, but we have achieved an important concession from Black. Black is no longer pressuring our center, and therefore, we get a free hand on the kingside. Moreover, closing the position is usually not the optimal strategy for the side with the bishop pair. Now, we have two important pawn breaks with b3 and e4. In some positions, we can combine both. } b5 
11. b3 ( { As usual, we try to undermine Black's pawn structure. } 11.a4 { is also possible, but Black can play } 11...b4 $5 { , when the game gets messy. } ) a6 ( { This move will likely transpose to } 11...Bb7 { . } ) 
12. a4 {[%mdl 32768]} Bb7 
13. axb5 { We have transposed to the 11...Bb7 variation [/variation/43294970/#/13/w]. } *

