1. d4 f5 { This is the beginning of the so-called Dutch Defense, which is very popular at the club level! } 
2. Nf3 { Our usual 2nd move, also effective against the Dutch Defense. In many cases, our idea will be to try to play for an early e4 break, sometimes supported by our beloved bishop on g5! Now, Black has several options. } Nf6 { The most common move by far! It makes sense; it's a normal developing move, and Black remains flexible with their structure. } 
3. Bg5 { What else? :) } e6 
4. Nbd2 Be7 
5. Bxf6 { Our main goal is to play e4, even at the expanse of exchanging our bishop. } Bxf6 
6. e4 { We've managed to play e4 in one go, and now Black has a few options. } fxe4 { Releasing the tension in the center can only help White. } 
7. Nxe4 {[%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1]} { Now Black has several options, which we'll analyze one by one. In general, we want to play Bd3 and castle short, with a very active position. } O-O 
8. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} { We are not interested in exchanging our powerful e4-knight, at least not just yet. } Nc6 
9. c3 { Our d4-pawn was under attack, so we can simply defend it. } d5 ( { Black needed to do something to active their light-squared bishop. If } 9...d6 10.h4 { with a powerful attack. } ) 
10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 
11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1g1]} ( { This move is slightly more accurate than } 11.O-O { because now we have stopped ...e5 once and for all. We can castle short next. } ) Bd7 
12. O-O $16  {[%cal Gf1e1,Ga1e1]} { White is clearly better with much better minor pieces. Black will never be able to play ...e5, as we can keep up the pressure on the e-file with Rae1 or Rfe1 next. } *

