1. d4 e6 
2. Nf3 c5 ( 2...c5 { This is a somewhat annoying move order! Now, all our usual moves have drawbacks, so we have to be creative. For players familiar with 1.e4, we can transpose to a main line Sicilian with } 3.e4! ) 
3. Bg5 { Did I say creative? Of course, Bg5 is our move. :) Let's see all possible responses by Black, one by one. } Qb6 
4. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} { This move is especially aimed against ...Qxb2. } d5 
5. e4 { This was the point: with three pieces now developed, Black is under pressure. The pawn on b2 can never be taken because of Nb5. Let's see a possible continuation. } dxe4 
6. Nxe4 cxd4 ( { Note that } 6...Qxb2? 7.dxc5 { leads to a decisive advantage for White since after } 7...Qb4+ 8.Nfd2 { , the black queen is not out of the woods yet, while the rest of Black's pieces are still on their initial squares. White's lead in development will continue to increase after moves such as Rb1, c3 followed by Nc4, etc. } ) 
7. Qxd4 Qxd4 
8. Nxd4 { We've reached a queenless middlegame where White is clearly better. } a6 { Necessary to stop Nb5 (or Bb5) ideas. } 
9. Be2 $16  {[%cal Ge1c1]} { With a clear advantage. You can see how we have developed all our four minor pieces whereas all Black's minor pieces are on their original squares! We'll probably castle long. } *

