1. d4 e6 
2. Nf3 c5 ( 2...c5 { This is a somewhat annoying move order! Now, all our usual moves have drawbacks, so we have to be creative. For players familiar with 1.e4, we can transpose to a main line Sicilian with } 3.e4! ) 
3. Bg5 { Did I say creative? Of course, Bg5 is our move. :) Let's see all possible responses by Black, one by one. } Qb6 
4. Nc3 { This move is especially aimed against ...Qxb2. } Qxb2 { We have to see what happens if Black takes on b2. } 
5. Bd2! {[%mdl 32768]} { This is a surprisingly strong move! } cxd4 
6. Rb1 Qa3 
7. Nb5 Qc5 
8. c3 dxc3 
9. Bxc3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gb5d6]} { All the previous moves were pretty much forced for Black, and it's clear that White has a strong compensation for the sacrificed pawns. Black hasn't developed any piece and will have a hard time containing our threats (e.g. Nd6+), and we can also slowly continue with e4 and castling short, bringing more pieces to the attack. } ( 9.Bxc3 { For instance, if } 9...a6 10.Nd6+ Qxd6 11.Qxd6 Bxd6 12.Bxg7 { . } ) Nc6 { The best move for Black, developing a piece without weakening any square. } 
10. Qd2 $14  {[%cal Gb5c7]} { We defend the c3-bishop and reactivate the Nc7+ threat, among others. } ( { Note that } 10.Nd6+ { is not effective now because of } 10...Bxd6 11.Bxg7 Qa5+ 12.Qd2 Qxd2+ 13.Nxd2 Be5 { since the e5-square is now defended by the c6-knight. } ) *

