{ José Camacho is one of my best friends, and he was key to the creation of this course. He is also an International Master and a professor at the University of Cardiff in Wales! } 1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 h6 
4. Bh4 { There we go following our recipe! } c5 
5. e3 b6 
6. Nc3 { With the idea of pushing d5 in many variations! } cxd4 
7. Nxd4 { Looking for the b5-square! } a6 
8. Qf3 Ra7 
9. Ne4 $5  ( 9.e4! { is our course recommendation [/variation/44718760/#/9/w]! } ) Be7 
10. Bxf6 Bxf6? ( { A clear mistake! } 10...gxf6 { was necessary, but White is slightly better after } 11.Qg3 { . } ) 
11. Nd6+ Ke7 
12. O-O-O! { This is probably what Black missed! } Qc7 ( 12...Kxd6? { loses because of } 13.Nc6+ { . } ) 
13. Bc4 ( 13.e4 { was even stronger: } 13...Nc6 14.Nxc6+ Qxc6 15.Qg3 { with the idea of going e5, supporting the d6-knight for the rest of the game. } ) Nc6 
14. Nxc6+ Qxc6 
15. e4 { Naturally, it's very important to avoid trading queens to take full advantage of the exposed king in the center of the board. } Qc5 
16. Rhe1! {[%cal Ge4e5]} { Very strong move by José, threatening e5! } b5 
17. Bb3? ( { José missed a nice chance to win the game with } 17.e5! Bg5+ 18.Kb1 Rf8 19.Bb3 { and Black's position is hopeless: Qg3 and f4 or h4 are coming! } ) Qe5 ( 17...Be5! { is a crazy and great defensive move! } 18.Qxf7+ Kd8 19.Nxc8 Kxc8 { and Black survives! } ) 
18. c3 Rc7 
19. Kb1 { No need to rush! White improves the king situation. } Rd8 
20. Qe3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} { Preparing f4. } Bg5 
21. Qb6? ( 21.Qe2! { is much stronger, with the simple idea of going g3 and f4, and Black can almost resign! } ) Qc5! 
22. Qa5 { The queen is a bit misplaced now! } Bf4? ( { This move can be punished now. } 22...Bb7! { was better } 23.g3 Kf8! { and the bishop can retreat to e7, when Black holds! } ) 
23. e5 Bb7 ( 23...Bxe5 24.Rxe5 Qxe5 25.Qxc7 $18 ) 
24. g3 {[%csl Rf4]} { Simple chess, trapping the bishop. } Bf3 
25. gxf4 Bxd1 
26. Rxd1 { And Black is lost. } Ra7 
27. Ne4 Qc6 
28. Qb4+ d6 
29. Nxd6 a5 
30. Nf5+ 1-0

