1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. Bg5 { There we go with our Torre Attack! } c5 
4. c3 d5 
5. e3 Nc6 
6. Nbd2 h6 
7. Bh4 { Always keeping the pin. } Be7 
8. Bd3 O-O 
9. O-O b6 
10. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4]} { Following our typical Torre Attack plan, intending to push f4. } Bb7 
11. Bxf6! { It makes sense to get rid of the dark-squared bishop if we have all our pawns on dark squares. With this move, we also eliminate one of the black king's defenders. } ( 11.f4 $5 { is also interesting, but Black gets a better version after } 11...Ne8 12.Bxe7 Nxe7 { followed by ...f6, with a decent position for Black. } ) Bxf6 
12. f4 g6 
13. Ndf3 { Bringing more pieces to the kingside party. Black cannot make use of the weak square on e4. } Bg7 
14. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} { Naturally, the idea is to destroy Black's pawn structure after h5! } Nxe5 
15. fxe5 { Opening up the f-file for White's heavy pieces. Black's position is terrible, especially because of the passive bishop on b7 and the lack of space. } a6 
16. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1g3]} { The queen can be transferred to g3. } Bc6 
17. Nh2 {[%cal Gh2g4][%csl Gf6]} { The queen on e1 makes this move possible since h4 is protected. The knight travels to g4, from where it puts an eye on the f6-square. } h5 { Stopping Ng4 has a drawback: White has created a contact point on g4, and g5 is a weak square as well. } 
18. Rf3 Bb5 
19. Bc2 { Why trade bishops? The white one is targeting g6 and attacking, whereas the black one on b5 is doing basically nothing, only covering f1. } Qe7 
20. Qf2 a5 
21. a4 Ba6 
22. Kh1 {[%cal Ga1g1,Gg2g4]} { We cannot use f1, so we make room for the rook on g1 to prepare for an eventual g4, blowing up the kingside. } Rab8 
23. Rg1 b5 { Trying to create counterplay on the quenside. The next move is extremely important for White. Can you see it? } 
24. Bd3 $3  { This is a fantastic prophylactic move, completely neutralizing the a6-bishop. } ( 24.g4? { is inaccurate } 24...bxa4 25.gxh5 { ( 25.Bb1 a3! is the point. 26.bxa3 Rxb1 27.Rxb1 Bd3 and the bishop arrives to the rescue! ) ` 1r3rk1/4qpb1/b3p1p1/p1ppP2P/p2P3P/2P1PR2/1PB2Q1N/6RK b - - 0 25 '  25...Rxb2 26.hxg6 fxg6 and suddenly Black is winning! } ) Qb7 ( 24...c4 25.Bb1 bxa4 26.g4 a3 27.bxa3 Rxb1 28.Rxb1 { and the bishop on a6 cannot contribute to the king's safety! That is why Bd3 is so subtle! } ) 
25. g4 bxa4 
26. Bxa6 Qxa6 
27. gxh5 { Black's position is just collapsing. } Qd3 
28. Ng4 Qe4 {[%cal Gb8b2][%csl Rf3]} { Threatening ...Rxb2. } 
29. Qg3 cxd4 ( 29...Rxb2 30.h6 Bh8 31.Nf2 Qc2 32.h5 { and g6 is falling! } ) 
30. h6 Bh8 
31. exd4 Rxb2 
32. h5 a3 
33. Nf2 Rxf2 ( 33...Qc2 34.h7+ Kxh7 35.hxg6+ { and White is winning. } ) 
34. Qxf2 { White is an exchange up and has stopped the a-pawn. } Rb8 
35. hxg6 fxg6 
36. Rf1 { Overprotecting the f3-rook so that the queen is free to move after ...Rb2. } Kh7 ( 36...Rb2 37.Qg3 { with the idea of Kg1! } ) 
37. Kg1 { Now the rook is free to finish the job! } Rb7 
38. Qg2 Qh4 
39. Rh3 Qe4 
40. Qxe4 dxe4 
41. Ra1 Rb3 
42. Kf2 {[%csl Rh8]} { The endgame is completely winning. Black is playing without the h8-bishop. } g5 
43. Rg3 Kg6 
44. Ke2 a4 
45. Rag1 a2 
46. Rxg5+ Kh7 
47. Ra1 Rxc3 
48. Rxa2 1-0

