1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. c3 Bd6 
4. Bg5 { This is our course recipe. } f6 
5. Bh4 Ne7 
6. Nbd2 Nf5 
7. Bg3 Nxg3 
8. hxg3 {[%csl Rh7]} { Black gets the bishop pair, but in return, if Black wants to stop e4, they will have to play ...f5, creating a weak square on e5. Also, the h-file has been opened and Black suffers on h7. } f5 
9. Ne5 O-O 
10. e3 { This is where our course analysis [/variation/43294858/#/10/w] ends. } Qe8 $6  ( 10...Nd7! { was needed to fight for equality: } 11.f4 Nf6 12.Bd3 { with a nice position. Ndf3 is coming! } ) 
11. f4 Nd7 
12. g4! { We want to open the b1-h7 diagonal for our light-squared bishop! } Nxe5 
13. fxe5 ( 13.dxe5 { was even stronger. } 13...Bc5 14.Qf3 { with the idea of going Qh3. Look at the c8-bishop, such a bad piece! } ) Be7 
14. Bd3 Qg6 
15. Qf3 { Black can't take on g4 twice because h7 is hanging. } c6 
16. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1g3,Gg3h5]} { White can transfer the knight all the way to h5! } h6 { After this move, Black threatens to take on g4. } 
17. gxf5 { This is necessary. } exf5 
18. Ng3 Be6 
19. Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4]} { The f4-square is very tasty for our knight! } Qf7 
20. Nf4 b5 { Black needs to create counterplay somewhere! } 
21. O-O-O b4 
22. cxb4 a5 
23. b5 { It's important to close files, even if it means giving up a pawn, to ensure our king's safety and allow White to focus on attacking the kingside. } cxb5 
24. Kb1 b4 
25. Rc1 { This is a good opportunity to use the c-file; Black faces significant difficulties placing a rook on c8 since after a trade, f5 can suffer after Nxe6. } Bg5 
26. Nxe6 Qxe6 
27. Rc5 {[%csl Ra5,Rd5,Rf5]} { And now Black can choose which pawn falls: a5, d5, or f5. :) } b3 
28. a3 { King safety! } Rad8 
29. Rxa5 f4 
30. e4 { The rest is easy. } Qb6 
31. Rxd5 Rxd5 
32. exd5 Qxd4 
33. Qe4 Qxe4 
34. Bxe4 Re8 
35. e6 Kf8 
36. Rh3 1-0

