14. Qh6 f6 
15. exf6 ( 15.Nf3! { is also interesting: } 15...fxe5 16.fxe5 { . Ideas: Rf2 followed by Raf1 and naturally, after ...Qg7, White can opt to trade queens or play Qg5. } ) Nxf6 {[%cal Gf6g4,Ge6e5]} { Black threatens ...Ng4 and ...e5 so White needs to be careful! } 
16. Qg5 { Parrying both threats. } a5 $6  {[%cal Gb7a6]} { I completely understand the idea. It is very human for Black to try to trade the ugly light-squared bishop with ...Ba6, but White can always push e4 after supporting the break with a rook! } 
17. Rae1! Ba6 
18. Bxa6 Rxa6 
19. e4! { The key move. } Qf7 
20. f5 { It makes sense to open some files since the black king is pretty exposed. } exf5 
21. exf5 b5 { Black tries to defend along the 6th rank with the rook. } 
22. fxg6 Qxg6 
23. Qe5 { Once again, it's very important to avoid trading queens since White has a better king. } Ra7 
