{ Once again, my friend and Professor José Camacho is in the house! } 1. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. d4 g6 
3. Bg5 Bg7 
4. Nbd2 O-O 
5. c3 d6 
6. e4 c5 
7. dxc5 dxc5 
8. Bc4 { Our recommendation. } Nc6 
9. O-O Qc7 { Stopping e5. } 
10. a4 h6 
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 
12. Re1 Bg7 
13. Qe2 { The idea is to support a possible e5. } a6 ( { This move isn't covered in our course; we only analyze } 13...Rd8 { and } ) ( 13...Bg4 { . } ) 
14. e5 { With this move, we restrict the g7-bishop. } Bg4 {[%cal Gc6e5]} { Black threatens ...Nxe5 now. } 
15. h3 ( 15.e6 $5 { is also interesting and the game remains very tense after } 15...f5 16.h3 Bh5 $13 { . } ) Bxf3 
16. Nxf3 e6! { This move is very important since White was threatening to go e6. } 
17. h4 $5  { I just love this move. I think it poses a lot of problems for Black in practice. No human on earth wants to allow h5. Once the diagonal is opened, White can set up nice machinery with Bd3 and Qe4, intending to penetrate on h7. If Black plays ...h5, the g5-square becomes weak, but even more importantly, there is a nice and new contact point on g4 for White. } h5 
18. Qe4! {[%cal Gg2g4]} { Centralizing and preparing g4! Black can never react with ...f6 since g6 and e6 will be very weak! } Rfd8 $6  ( 18...Rab8 { , the engine has steel nerves and wants to proceed calmly on the queenside. } ) 
19. g4! hxg4 
20. Qxg4 Na5? ( { Now the knight is completely out of play. } 20...Nxe5 { was necessary, but Black's position is tough to play after } 21.Nxe5 Bxe5 22.h5 Kg7! 23.hxg6 fxg6 24.Bxe6 { , when White is the one putting pressure here! } ) 
21. Ba2 Qb6 
22. h5 { Let's finish the job! } gxh5 
23. Qxh5 {[%cal Gf3g5]} { Ng5 is coming now. } c4 
24. Ng5 Rd7 
25. Rad1 Rad8 
